@article{Carnahan1990,
abstract = {The urban heat island effect is recognized as a common and pervasive urban climatological phenomenon. Here the less common phenomenon of an urban heat sink is examined with respect to the mechanism which might explain its formation. Thematic Mapper (TM) data for a study area of central Indiana, including the Indianapolis metropolitan area, are employed in an effort to assess the heat sink in both qualitative and quantitative terms. The phenomenon is found to be regionally pervasive under specific conditions, and quite strong (6.4°C in our central Indiana case study). Explanations of the phenomenon are sought in the temporal and surface characteristics within the study area. A number of factors have contributed to the phenomenon: time and date of data acquisition, climatological conditions relating to soil moisture and air temperature, and agricultural land preparation relating to soil density. More specific understanding of the anomalous urban heat sink is sought through an examination of urban versus rural emissivity variations. Although it is an important variable, emissivity variation does not account for the magnitude of the heat sink gradient that we have observed. The anomaly within our study area and its magnitude can only be understood with reference to low thermal inertia (and consequent low conductivity) of the soil, which in turn are the result of specific observable conditions: dry, bare, and low density soil. {\textcopyright} 1990.},
