@article{Hunt2011,
abstract = {Developing a theoretical description of turbulent plumes, the likes$\backslash$nof which may be seen rising above industrial chimneys, is a daunting$\backslash$nthought. Plumes are ubiquitous on a wide range of scales in both$\backslash$nthe natural and the man-made environments. Examples that immediately$\backslash$ncome to mind are the vapour plumes above industrial smoke stacks$\backslash$nor the ash plumes forming particle-laden clouds above an erupting$\backslash$nvolcano. However, plumes also occur where they are less visually$\backslash$napparent, such as the rising stream of warmair above a domestic radiator,$\backslash$nof oil from a subsea blowout or, at a larger scale, of air above$\backslash$nthe so-called urban heat island. In many instances, not only the$\backslash$nplume itself is of interest but also its influence on the environment$\backslash$nas a whole through the process of entrainment. Zeldovich (1937, The$\backslash$nasymptotic laws of freely-ascending convective flows. Zh. Eksp. Teor.$\backslash$nFiz., 7, 1463{\^{a}}1465 (in Russian)), Batchelor (1954, Heat convection$\backslash$nand buoyancy effects in fluids. Q. J. R. Meteor. Soc., 80, 339{\^{a}}358)$\backslash$nand Morton et al. (1956, Turbulent gravitational convection from$\backslash$nmaintained and instantaneous sources. Proc. R. Soc. Lond. A, 234,$\backslash$n1{\^{a}}23) laid the foundations for classical plume theory, a theoretical$\backslash$ndescription that is elegant in its simplicity and yet encapsulates$\backslash$nthe complex turbulent engulfment of ambient fluid into the plume.$\backslash$nTestament to the insight and approach developed in these early models$\backslash$nof plumes is that the essential theory remains unchanged and is widely$\backslash$napplied today. We describe the foundations of plume theory and link$\backslash$nthe theoretical developments with the measurements made in experiments$\backslash$nnecessary to close these models before discussing some recent developments$\backslash$nin plume theory, including an approach which generalizes results$\backslash$nobtained separately for the Boussinesq and the non-Boussinesq plume$\backslash$ncases. The theory presented{\^{a}}despite its simplicity{\^{a}}has been very$\backslash$nsuccessful at describing and explaining the behaviour of plumes across$\backslash$nthe wide range of scales they are observed. We present solutions$\backslash$nto the coupled set of ordinary differential equations (the plume$\backslash$nconservation equations) that Morton et al. (1956) derived from the$\backslash$nNavier{\^{a}}Stokes equations which govern fluid motion. In order to$\backslash$ndescribe and contrast the bulk behaviour of rising plumes from general$\backslash$narea sources, we present closed-form solutions to the plume conservation$\backslash$nequations that were achieved by solving for the variation with height$\backslash$nof Morton's non-dimensional flux parameter {\^{I}}{\^{a}}this single flux$\backslash$nparameter gives a unique representation of the behaviour of steady$\backslash$nplumes and enables a characterization of the different types of plume.$\backslash$nWe discuss advantages of solutions in this form before describing$\backslash$nextensions to plume theory and suggesting directions for new research.},
